“The sea is ours”: Bolivia, a country without a coastline, hopes the court will open the way to the Pacific
Sailors patrol a rig-covered naval headquarters in La Paz.
Public buildings raise a sea blue flag.
Marine bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon are decorated with the motto: “We have the right to the sea.
It is our duty to recover it.”
The entire inland state of Bolivia still has a fresh memory of the coastline it lost to Chile during a bloody resource conflict in the 19th century, and the country longs to be able to sail once again on the Pacific Ocean.
These hopes may be greater than they have been for decades, with Bolivia awaiting a ruling from the International Court of Justice on October 1 after five years of deliberation.
“Bolivia has the drive, the spirit of community and peace of mind, and of course awaits the result with a positive attitude,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will see the ruling of the International Court of Justice on the big screen in many different places in the country, hoping that the court in The Hague will give its ruling in favor of Bolivia’s claim that Chile – after decades of sporadic negotiations – is obliged to negotiate to give Bolivia a separate outlet to the sea.
Evo Morales, Bolivia’s charismatic native president – facing a controversial re-election campaign next year – has also staked heavily on Monday’s verdict.
“We are very close to a return to the Pacific,” he promised in late August.
But some analysts believe that the court will hardly take Bolivia’s side, and that very little would change if it did.
The UN body, like the team in the Netherlands, has no authority to allow them to give away Chilean lands, and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of any negotiations.
The ruling by the International Court of Justice comes just six months after the last arguments were heard, saying the case was “not complicated,” according to Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law.
And rather than advancing the cause of Bolivia, the last four years may have actually made things worse.
“The problem of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian administration,” Zárate said.
She believes that Morales’ antagonistic rhetoric has squandered any remaining goodwill on Chile’s side.
Bolivia and Chile will continue negotiations at some point, but it will be extremely difficult to discuss the matter after this.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia's representative at The Hague, rejected the theory that the court's decision came unusually quickly.
On Monday, he said, Bolivia will offer “an extraordinary opportunity to open a new generation of relations with Chile” and the opportunity to “stop 139 years of disagreement, for the benefit of both parties.”
Calzadilla also denied that Morales, who is still one of Latin America’s most popular presidents, has used the maritime situation as a political cover-up.
"Bolivia will never give up its right to have access to the Pacific," he added.
“The feeling is an opportunity to see what we have to do to overcome the past.”
