Scotland’s free schools are constantly exhibiting academic excellence, and this has persisted in 2018 with another year of outstanding exam results. These are underpinned by individual and joint success in sports, art, music and other community activities.
These schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools, have more than 30,000 students across Scotland, and work hard to deliver the very best school experience to both students and parents.
Free schools aim to prepare their students for further and higher education, their chosen careers and their position as world citizens.
As an educational body that can design and implement a tailored school curriculum, we see that modern languages are still a popular and in demand elective at schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, the words hit his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, the words reach his heart.”
This is a powerful reminder that we can’t just stick to English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From this year’s exam results, we see that language is at the top of the table with the highest pass percentages from free schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages received the exam grade A.
The data, collected from 74 member schools of the Free School Council, showed that 72 percent of students received the exam grade A in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who studied German, 69 percent of those who studied French and 63 percent of those who studied Spanish also received A.
This illustrates that free schools in Scotland support foreign languages as a crucial skill children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages as subject choices are now valued at the same level as real-life subjects such as science, technology, engineering and mathematics on the curriculum for free schools and elsewhere.
A survey conducted by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014 found that 17 percent of the reasons employers stated to have difficulty in occupying a vacancy could be attributed to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly important in preparing young people for a future career.
As more and more job opportunities require language skills, these skills become crucial in a globalized world.
If you have learned a second language, these lifelong skills will bring real benefits in the future, no matter what career you choose.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically give a multilingual person a competitive advantage.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation, and French was the only language a two-digit number of participants (15 percent) could speak.
This is why investing in language education is now crucial for today’s children.
Knowing more languages, especially those related to emerging economies, will give children better opportunities to find good jobs.
In Scotland if each school teach in different languages.
Many schools will focus on the more classical modern languages, while others will teach in the languages that are considered most valuable to the UK on the way towards 2020, such as Mandarin and Japanese.
Whatever interests your child, there will always be a choice of languages to choose from at free schools, with teachers who are experts in this field.
Scottish Free Schools aim to create a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the knowledge and skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future brings.
In today’s global business environment, it cannot be denied that languages are still crucial to the country’s future, and this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should in fact be considered as “international communication skills”.
Free schools will continue to offer this opportunity, diversity and distinction for Scotland’s youth.
We have to do it.
