North Korea will not agree to unilateral disarmament without confidence
North Korea’s foreign minister told the UN on Saturday that continued sanctions strengthened distrust of the United States and that the country would in no way agree to unilaterally release its nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the World Organization’s annual general assembly that North Korea has implemented “significant benevolent measures” over the past year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test area and vowing not to proliferate nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
“We haven’t seen a similar response from the United States,” he said.
Without confidence in the United States, we have no confidence in our national security, and under such circumstances we will under no circumstances unilaterally disarm ourselves first.
Ri repeated well-known North Korean complaints about Washington’s opposition to a gradual nuclear disarmament, in which North Korea is rewarded for gradual stages of disarmament, but his statement was significant because it did not reject unilateral nuclear disarmament completely, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump in Singapore on June 12, at the very first meeting between a sitting president of the United States and a North Korean leader, in which Kim vowed to work against “nuclear disarmament of the Korean Peninsula” while Trump guaranteed North Korea’s security.
North Korea has called for a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must first release its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also opposed calls to reduce stringent international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'nuclear disarmament first', raising pressure via sanctions to achieve its goal by force, and even opposes the 'declaration of the end of the war'," Ri said.
“The belief that sanctions can force us to kneel is a dream for people who don’t know anything about us.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions create further mistrust.”
Ri did not mention the plans for a second meeting between Kim and Trump that the US leader stressed before the UN earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae over the past five months, adding: “If the other party in this disarmament case were South Korea, rather than the United States, the nuclear disarmament of the Korean Peninsula would not have been as firm as it is.”
However, the tone of Ri’s speech was very different from last year’s, when he told the UN General Assembly that an attack on the mainland U.S. with North Korea’s missiles was inevitable after “Mr. Evil President” Trump called Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
After threatening to “completely destroy” North Korea last year, Trump stood in front of the UN this year and praised Kim for being brave enough to take disarmament steps, but said much work remains to be done and sanctions must remain in place until North Korea is nuclear-armed.
On Wednesday, Trump saw that he did not have a time frame for this, saying, “It doesn’t matter if it takes two years, three years or five months.”
China and Russia believe that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures taken.
But US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday: “The Security Council’s sanctions must continue to be enforced vigorously and without exception until we have achieved complete, final and confirmed nuclear disarmament.”
The Security Council has unanimously increased sanctions against North Korea since 2006 to curb funding for Pyongyang’s nuclear and missile weapons program.
Pompeo met Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly, after which he said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a new summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but the last trip did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July, saying that they had made progress, but only hours after North Korea accused him of making “small claims.”
North Korea pledged in a meeting with Moon this month to shut down a missile area as well as a nuclear weapons facility if the U.S. took “equivalent action.”
He said Kim had said that these “equivalent measures” he wants were security guarantees Trump promised in Singapore and measures to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard Students Take Courses in Getting Enough Rest
A new course at Harvard University this year will help students get more sleep by tackling the growing inculturation of caffeinated drinks as fuel.
One academic found that students at the world’s best university often had no idea how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, prepared the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He started the course after he gave a lecture on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“After the lecture, a girl came to me and said, ‘Why has no one said this before?’
She said no one had ever told her how important sleep was, and that surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which starts this year, explains to students how important it is to have good sleep habits in order to be able to perform academically and sportively, and for the general condition.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to start the course after seeing students suffering from severe sleep deprivation.
The course, which lasts for one hour, has a series of interactive tasks.
In one part there is a picture of a room in a dormitory, where students can click on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers and books and learn about the effects of caffeine and light and how sports performance is affected by lack of sleep, and how important it is with a sleep routine.
In another part, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A map of the campus with interactive icons makes participants think about their own daily routine.
“We are aware that this is not going to change the behavior of students immediately.
But we believe that they have the right to know about this, just as you have the right to know about the risks of smoking,” said Professor Czeisler.
There is still some pride in being able to pee all night, he said, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students led to sleep deprivation being an increasing problem.
Enough and good sleep should be the students’ “secret weapon” against stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said – even as a means of weight gain, as lack of sleep puts the brain in starvation mode, leading to a constant feeling of hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old from California who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler prepare the course. He took one of the professor’s classes last year, his first year at Harvard.
He said the course inspired him to work for a course that was available to the entire campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all master’s students to take a similar study program before enrolling in the university.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students put on an alarm for when to go to bed as well as for when to get up, and that they should be aware of the harmful effects of blue light from electronic displays and LED lights. This type of light can disrupt the circadian rhythm and lead to sleep difficulties.
