The National Trust listens to the secret lives of bats
New research conducted at a country estate in the Scottish Highlands will reveal how bats use the landscape in search of food.
It is hoped that the findings will shed new light on the behaviour of the unique flying mammals and help shape future conservation measures.
The study by researchers at the National Trust for Scotland will follow common bats and dwarf bats as well as brown moose and water bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at important locations around the property to track bat activity throughout the season.
NHS personnel and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
Expert sound analyses of all recordings will determine the frequency of bat screams and which species do what.
Then a habitat map and a report will be prepared to create a detailed landscape picture of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by each of the species.
This information will be included in the decision on what measures to implement, such as planting pastures and how best to take care of the forest for bats and other associated species.
The population of bats in Scotland and the United Kingdom has declined considerably over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and construction work that affects brood sites and habitat restriction.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, the same with flypaper and certain chemically treated building materials as well as attacks from house cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
But because of their nocturnal hunting habits, they have more need for their ears than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use advanced echolocation to find insects and obstacles on the road as they fly.
NTS, which is responsible for the maintenance of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 acres of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
They have ten skilled experts who regularly carry out surveys, mapping of brood sites and sometimes rescue work.
The organization has also established Scotland’s first and only own flagge reserve at Threave Land Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland’s ten flagge species.
Property manager David Thompson says the property is the ideal territory for them.
“Here at Threave we have a perfect area for bats,” he says.
“We have the old buildings, a lot of old trees and the ideal habitat.
But there’s still a lot we don’t know about bats, so the work we do here and at other properties will help us understand more about what they need to thrive.”
He stresses the importance of mapping bats before maintenance is carried out on a property since the unintentional destruction of a single breeding site can kill up to 400 females and young, and perhaps exterminate an entire local population.
Bats are protected, and it is illegal to kill them, harass or disturb them or destroy their breeding sites.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish employee of the Bat Conservation Trust, has urged the public to help with the work.
She says: “We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many of the species we simply don’t know how their populations are doing.”
