Algae bloom update: Concentrations reduced in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Commission on Fisheries and Wildlife (FWC) shows a general decline in red algae concentrations for parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, spotted blooms are reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier County – suggesting reduced concentrations.
A bloom of red algae extends about 210 km along the coast, from the north in Pinellas to the south in Lee County.
Spots are detected about 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but fewer spots than last week.
Red algae have also been observed in Pasco County.
There have been reports of medium concentrations at or off the coast of Pinellas County in the last week, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, natural to high concentrations in Manatee County, natural to high concentrations at or off the coast of Sarasota County, natural to medium concentrations in Charlotte County, natural to medium concentrations in Charlotte County.
Airway irritation is still reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier County.
There have been no reports of airway irritation in northwest Florida over the past week.
